ted coverage gaps, and its project-rule scanner erodes the speed advantage. Also **no Markdown support**, so prettier stays for SPEC/CHANGELOG/AGENTS anyway — meaning Biome wouldn't even eliminate a tool, just add a second formatter with drift risk.\n\nNeither tool replaces prettier for `.md`, so **prettier stays as the formatter regardless** (oxfmt is 0.x and JS/TS-only). The right shape is: oxlint for linting, prettier standalone for formatting — which also deletes `eslint-plugin-prettier` from api and its 30% rule-time tax.\n\n## What a migration costs / loses\n\n- **`baseUrl` must go from api's tsconfig** — tsgo (TS7) removed it. I already verified it's safe: it's just the NestJS template default, nothing imports through it, `tsc --noEmit` is green without it.\n- **`turbo/no-undeclared-env-vars` has no native oxlint port** — it did catch the `NEXT_RUNTIME`/`CI` omissions yesterday. oxlint's JS-plugin compat (alpha) can likely run it; otherwise accept the loss or keep it as a pre-commit-only micro-eslint. Low value, decide in the PR.\n- **tsgolint is still 0.x** (\"preview\"): 2 of 61 rules missing, possible behavior drift from typescript-eslint on edge cases. For a repo this size the risk is small and CI would catch regressions in what matters.\n- One-time config translation across 3 workspaces + a review of rule-diff noise (the raw run already shows a handful of new findings like `unicorn/prefer-set-size` — triage during migration).\n\nExpected end state: `turbo lint` for the whole repo in **~2s including type-aware api**, no OOM, no `--concurrency=1` ritual, prettier check ~6s unchanged. Given how many times lint runs per agent session in your overnight loops, this pays for itself quickly — that's the actual leverage, not human keystrokes.\n\nWant me to do the migration PR (oxlint + tsgolint, drop eslint/eslint-plugin-prettier, `baseUrl` removal, prettier `format:check` in CI)?",
